Basic Linux Commands (with simple descriptions)
#	Command	Description
1	pwd	Prints current working directory path.
2	ls	Lists files & folders in current directory.
3	man ls	Displays manual (help page) for ls command.
4	cd <directory>	Changes to a specified directory.
5	touch filename	Creates a new empty file.
6	mkdir <directory>	Creates a new directory (folder).
7	rm filename	Removes (deletes) a file.
8	mv source destination	Moves or renames a file/folder.
9	ifconfig	Shows network interface details.
10	cat filename	Displays content of a file.
11	cp source destination	Copies a file from source to destination.
12	grep <keyword> filename	Finds & highlights keyword in a file.
13	ping google.com	Checks internet connectivity by pinging Google.
14	whoami	Displays current username.
15	sudo su	Switches to root user (superuser mode).
16	sudo apt install <package>	Installs a software package. Example: sudo apt install netcat.

âœ… How to Run These Commands (Example Flow):
Open Terminal (Ctrl + Alt + T).

Type:
pwd
ls
mkdir testfolder
cd testfolder
touch myfile.txt
cat myfile.txt

To install a package (e.g., netcat):

sudo apt update
sudo apt install netcat
